title: The Art Lecture Series - Sacred Trees of India: Photography by Deidi von Schaewen
body:
Free to the public, Evergreen's visual arts and writing programs offer an opportunity to hear local, national and international interdisciplinary artists, writers and art workers speak about their work. The fall 2014 series will present a diverse and interesting lineup. Artists were chosen (albeit loosely) with the year's theme of "paying attention" in mind. The theme comes from the orientation book, "Crow Planet" by Lyanda Lynn Haupt.

Artist lecture
Sacred Trees of India: Photographs by Deidi von Schaewen

For the past 28 years, von Schaewen has traveled in India, immersing herself in its people and culture, and exploring themes through her photography and video. For her series on the Sacred Trees, she traveled the length and breadth of India. The exhibition in Evergreen Gallery is an opportunity to view these lush, complex images in large-scale, to be surrounded by their energy and power.

Born in Berlin, von Schaewen studied painting at the Berlin Academy of Arts before deciding to concentrate on photography and film. Currently she is based in Paris. She has exhibited extensively throughout Europe, India, North Africa, and the US. Twenty books of her photographs have been published, with one about Sacred Trees of India due out next year. A continuing obsession of hers is to capture on film the ephemeral, aspects of our urban and rural civilizations that are temporary, fleeting, or vanishing with time. For the Sacred Trees of India, it is more a revelation of devotion and accumulation over time, the ability of trees to survive, rejuvenate, transform – in India, trees are not only sacred to the gods, they can actually BE gods.

Von Schaewen was director of photography for a feature film by Robert Cordier in 1972 – a time when it was unusual for a woman to be in that position. She continued as director of photography on other films, and in 1978 she

title: Sacred Trees of India: Photographs by Deidi von Schaewen - Exhibition Opening Reception
body:
Exhibition opening reception
Sacred Trees of India: Photographs by Deidi von Schaewen

Evergreen Gallery is extremely pleased to announce the fall exhibition, Sacred Trees of India: Photographs by Deidi von Schaewen. For the past 28 years, von Schaewen has traveled in India, immersing herself in its people and culture, and exploring themes through her photography and video. For her series on the Sacred Trees, she traveled the length and breadth of India. The exhibition in Evergreen Gallery is an opportunity to view these lush, complex images in large-scale, to be surrounded by their energy and power.

Born in Berlin, von Schaewen studied painting at the Berlin Academy of Arts before deciding to concentrate on photography and film. Currently she is based in Paris. She has exhibited extensively throughout Europe, India, North Africa, and the US. Twenty books of her photographs have been published, with one about Sacred Trees of India due out next year. A continuing obsession of hers is to capture on film the ephemeral, aspects of our urban and rural civilizations that are temporary, fleeting, or vanishing with time. For the Sacred Trees of India, it is more a revelation of devotion and accumulation over time, the ability of trees to survive, rejuvenate, transform – in India, trees are not only sacred to the gods, they can actually BE gods.

Von Schaewen was director of photography for a feature film by Robert Cordier in 1972 – a time when it was unusual for a woman to be in that position. She continued as director of photography on other films, and in 1978 she began writing and directing her own films. One of her films, Sravanabelgola, will be showing in Evergreen Gallery as part of the exhibition.

For more information, please visit www.evergreen.edu/gallery.

title: How to choose a college that’s a good fit for you
body: As a collaboration between South Puget Sound Community College, The Evergreen State College and Saint Martin’s University, this event is the first of three College Planning Seminars held for local high school students, their families and counselors. These workshops will highlight the differences between the three different types of institutions: a public two-year community college, a public four-year college, and a private four-year university while covering the topics of college “fit”, financial aid and the college application. All three sessions are free and open to the public, no reservation is required. For more information, visit http://www.stmartin.edu/admissions/undergraduate/Southsound.aspx or call Clarisse Leong at St. Martin's: (360) 867-6170.

title: A talk by an Evergreen alumna on "Learning from nature using a computational chemistry approach"
body:
Metal-containing proteins play a central role in the activation of energy-relevant small molecules by biological systems. This talk will describe current synergistic research at Pacific Northwest National Laboratory in collaboration with academic institutions that aims to unravel how metal proteins regulate catalytic aspects of metalloenzymatic systems, specifically hydrogenase for conversion of protons and electrons into dihydrogen, methyl coenzyme M reductase for production of methanol from methane, and nitrogenase for synthesis of ammonia from dinitrogen. Evolution has optimized these enzymes to maximize reactant specificity and stabilize reaction intermediates while operating under ambient conditions of temperature and pressure. Our ultimate aim is to learn from nature to design bio-inspired molecular catalysts to replace the energy-intensive processes used today by leveraging biochemical characterization, inorganic synthesis and computational chemistry. This talk will focus on the latter, describing multi-scale computational chemistry applications that resolve key scientific questions about the role of protein structure and dynamics underlying biological catalytic mechanisms with regards to electron, proton and substrate delivery, protein dynamics, and reaction thermodynamics using state-of-the art applications of quantum, classical and statistical physics and high-performance computing.

For more information on the event, please contact Dharshi Bopegedera at ext. 6620, bopegedd@evergreen.edu

title: Willi Unsoeld Seminar Series - Mark Bittner, Author of The Wild Parrots of Telegraph Hill
body:
Renowned for his book, The Wild Parrots of Telegraph Hill: A Love Story, Mark Bittner is the first speaker in the Willi Unsoeld Seminar Series at The Evergreen State College, on October 30. The event, which takes place at 7pm in the campus Longhouse, follows the college’s 2014-15 academic theme of “Paying Attention.” Bittner will discuss a period when, as a street person in San Francisco, he developed an affinity with a (still-vital) flock of wild parrots inhabiting Telegraph Hill. The book went on to become a documentary film and Bittner has gone on to write his forthcoming book Street Song, a memoir.

According to Evergreen Vice President and Provost Michael Zimmerman, “the purpose of these lectures is to help us see things in new ways and across differences. Willi used to say the most important thing is how we treat each other… and by extension the way we treat our surroundings,” said Zimmerman. “Mark Bittner was seeing things in a way that others were missing. His message of discovery is important to us.”

Willi Unsoeld is a household name among mountaineers, famed for his first ascent of Mt. Everest’s West Ridge in 1963, but Unsoeld had a deep intellectual life beyond the sport of climbing. As a philosopher and founding faculty member at The Evergreen State College, Unsoeld embodied the interdisciplinary spirit of the college. After his death in 1979, the Unsoeld family, friends and colleagues created a legacy in his name for an annual seminar series to take place at Evergreen. Past speakers have included Jim Hightower, Yevgeny Yevtushenko, Terry Tempest Williams, Tom Hornbein and The International Council of Thirteen Indigenous Grandmothers.

This event is free and open to the public (excluding parking costs). For additional information, please see the press release: http://www.evergreen.edu/news/2014/willi-unsoeld-seminar-series.htm

title: Oil & Water Documentary and Talks
body:
“OIL & WATER” Screening at Lecture Hall 1; Meet the Evergreen grad filmmaker

With Cofan Chief Randy Borman
The filmmaker: Evergreen Alum Laurel Spellman Smith
Various regional tribal members

Oil & Water is the coming of age story of two boys as they each confront one of the world’s worst toxic disasters. Hugo comes to America to fight for the survival of his tribe in the Ecuadorian Amazon, while David goes to Ecuador to launch the world’s first company to certify oil as “fair trade.” Can Hugo become the leader his tribe so desperately wants him to be? Will David clean up one of the world's dirtiest industries? This documentary film is an intimate portrait of two young people finding their voices and trying to beat incredible odds. Their journeys lead them to explore what could be a more just future, not just for the people of the Amazon, but for all people around the world born with oil beneath their feet. Eight years in the making, Oil & Water is a shocking and inspiring David and Goliath story. For background on the film, see www.oilandwaterdocumentary.com

Winner: Jury & Audience Awards - BEST DOCUMENTARY - Northampton International Film Festival Winner: Grand Prize - BEST DOCUMENTARY - Audience Award at Rhode Island International Film Festival Winner: GREEN PLANET Award - Rhode Island International Film Festival

Zoltan Grossman (faculty) and Micah McCarty (Special Assistant to the President on Tribal Relations) will make brief introductions about the significance of this film, in reflection of related fossil-fuel topics currently facing North American Indigenous peoples.

We will be holding a potluck-style reception in another room, to immediately follow the Q. & A. at the end of the screening.

Classes are welcome;
please inform Micah at mccartmi@evergreen.edu
and Zoltan at grossmaz@evergreen.edu
Free and open to the campus and Olympia community.
room: Lecture Hall 1 - The Evergreen State College, Olympia, WA
repeat: Monday, November 3, 2014 - 3:30 pm to 6:00 pm

title: Lecture by Author and Evergreen Grad, Chris Dixon
body:
Chris Dixon will be speaking about the ideas in his just published book, Another Politics, on TUESDAY, NOVEMBER 4th, 10 AM-11:30 AM in Library 4300.

Drawing on interviews with dozens of experienced organizers, Chris Dixon in his just published, "Another Politics: Talking Across Today’s Transformative Movements" engages the convergence of anti-authoritarian radicalism and broader-based movements in the U.S. and Canada. From this convergence, a growing set of
activists – from anti-poverty organizers in Toronto to prison abolitionists in Oakland, from occupy activists in New York to migrant justice organizers in Vancouver – are developing shared politics and practices. These efforts combine anti-authoritarian, anti-capitalist, anti-oppression politics with grassroots organizing among ordinary,
non-activist people. Another Politics explores these efforts and distills lessons for building effective, visionary movements. For more information about the book, see http://writingwithmovements.com/another-politics.

BIO:
Chris, originally from Alaska, is a longtime anarchist organizer, writer, and educator with a PhD from the University of California at Santa Cruz. He graduated form Evergreen in 1999. His writing has appeared in numerous book collections as well as periodicals such as Anarchist Studies, Clamor, Left Turn, and Social Movement Studies. He serves on the board of the Institute for Anarchist Studies and the advisory board for the activist journal Upping the Anti. Dixon lives in Ottawa, Canada, on unceded Algonquin Territory, where he is involved in anti-poverty organizing. Find him at http://writingwithmovements.com.

P.S. Besides his 10 AM talk in Lib 4300 on Tuesday, November 4th, Chris Dixon will also be reading from his book, Tuesday evening at ORCA Books, 509 E. 4th, downtown Olympia
room: Library 4300, The Evergreen State College, Olympia, WA

title: Not a Lecture: Eric Jarosinski, editor of NeinQuarterly, Goodwill Tour
body: This public event is open to all and sponsored by Structures and Strictures and Small Things coordinated studies programs, and the Academic Deans. Is the Tour a Lecture? Nein. Its negative utopian potential is often best realized as a conversation with a moderator, some visuals, possibly music, and a theme. THEORY AS TRAGEDY, PRAXIS AS FARCE. A CIVILIZATION OF DISCONTENTS. THIS IS NOT A PIPE. Is the Tour art? Nein. It is, however, a performance of sorts. An aesthetic and intellectual experiment only slightly less pretentious than it sounds. It has been called the death of the academy. Somewhat entertaining. Moderately edifying. And the dawn of a new age.

title: Electronic Music Collective presents Midnight Aurora
body:
The EMC Presents:

A electronic music event to remember.

This night shall be one of revelry. Join us and let go for one night. Winter is upon us and the darkness that follows often consumes us. We strive to provide the ultimate event for letting go and reminding yourself where happiness thrives.

Midnight Aurora features some of the best local DJs the pacific northwest has to offer. With 15,000 watts of sound, and full 3D mapping, you're sure to have a time to remember.

Doors at 7pm
Ends at 2am

Tickets:
$2 General Admission - Purchased at Door.

The Evergreen State College.

Olympia, Washington 98505

Library Building - Top Floor.

Zero-tolerance policy

Subject to bagcheck

title: Evergreen Dance Co-op
body:
This is a community dance event with a long history at Evergreen. It is a safe space for the practice of 5 Rhythms and our own personal dance practices. The Evergreen Dance Co-op is dedicated to supporting and empowering the community through dance. In order for us to be free to express ourselves fully we ask all participants to agree to these community guidelines: we do not wear shoes or talk on the dance floor, we maintain a substance-free space, and we respect the dance (please participate fully!).

This is an event sponsored by the Evergreen Dance Co-op.

If accommodation is required for this event, please contact Student Activities with reasonable advance notice by emailing StudentActivities@evergreen.edu or by calling (360) 867-6220 or (360) 867-6834 (TTY).

title: Riot to Follow Theater Productions presents The Oy of Sex
body:
After leaving her cheating husband, Bea discovers, to her horror, that her nice Jewish son Hal has secretly been running a sex shop in London's Soho district. When Hal closes up shop for a two-week holiday, his prudish mum insists upon smartening-up the ramshackle store while he's gone. Afraid to lose sales in the meantime, she finds she has a flare for counseling the lonely customers who wander in -- and for selling them sex toys.

MATURE CONTENT

Please email rtftheaterproductions@gmail.com with any questions!

title: Willi Unsoeld Seminar Series - Audrey Marrs, Documentary Filmmaker
body:
Oscar winning documentary filmmaker Audrey Marrs, will be the second speaker in the Willi Unsoeld Seminar Series at The Evergreen State College on January 29. Famed for her 2011 Oscar winner, “Inside Job,” Marrs graduated Evergreen in 1996. A collaboration with director Charles Ferguson, Inside Job was a 2010 Official Selection at the Cannes, New York, Telluride and Toronto International Film Festivals. Wesley Morris of The Boston Globe called it, "scarier than anything Wes Craven and John Carpenter have ever made…"

Additional information on this event will be provided very soon. Watch this space for details: http://www.evergreen.edu/news/2014/willi-unsoeld-seminar-series.htm

title: Robert Egger, founder of the DC Central Kitchen, Liberal Arts Forum
body:
Evening and Weekend Studies and the President’s Diversity Fund welcome Robert Egger, founder of the innovative social justice/food justice nonprofit, DC Central Kitchen, on February 4.

Robert will be our featured speaker at the Evening and Weekend Liberal Arts Forum in the Longhouse, from 6-9 pm on Wednesday, February 4, on "The Power of Community." For the past 25 years, Egger has been challenging the way nonprofits think about their work, how Americans view the homeless and how food is used to help men and women escape poverty. Join us for a provocative, inspirational dialogue about the role you can play in changing your community.

Please join us. Guests are quite welcome.
room: The Evergreen State College, Olympia, WA - Evergreen Longhouse

title: An Info Session on Cultivating Voice
body:
Students interested in becoming a peer tutor at the Writing Center are required to take a two-credit course, Cultivating Voice: A Writing Tutor's Craft, offered every Spring. Students interested in taking this course are strongly encouraged to attend our Winter Quarter info-session, where you'll get a taste of what the class entails, have the opportunity to ask questions, and recieve your application to apply for the class.

This info session will be offered on February 18th & 19th, from 4-5pm, in LIB 1005.

Cultivating Voice combines readings, reflective writing, seminar, and a practicum to prepare students to become peer tutors in the Writing Centers. In seminar, students explore tutoring theories, examine the role of a peer tutor and develop effective tutoring practices. In the practicum, students will observe peer tutoring and graduate to supervised tutoring. The course also will address racial and social justice in serving and working with a diverse group. Students considering graduate school in related fields like education, creative writing, and literature will benefit from this training. Please refer to the Academic Catalog﻿ for the current academic year for more information.

title: JUSTICE RISING: FROM PALESTINE TO FERGUSON, FROM FIRST NATIONS TO THE US BORDERLANDS
body:
“JUSTICE RISING: FROM PALESTINE TO FERGUSON, FROM FIRST NATIONS TO THE US BORDERLANDS”

Feb. 23, 2015
Peace Works 2015 with Omar Barghouti

DAY EVENTS:

12:00 – 1:00, Lecture Hall I “The BDS Movement Explained” With author and cofounder of the BDS movement (Boycott, Divestment, Sanctions) Omar Barghouti.
1:30 – 3:00, Seminar II – E1105 “Gaza in Arizona: How Israeli High Tech Firms will Up-Armor the U.S.- Mexican Border” Workshop with Gabriel Schivone
3:30 – 5:00 Seminar II – E1107 “Conversations on BDS” Workshop with Students for Justice in Palestine

MAIN EVENING EVENT:
7:00 – 9:00 - Evergreen Longhouse
“JUSTICE RISING: FROM PALESTINE TO FERGUSON, FROM FIRST NATIONS TO THE US BORDERLANDS”

A panel discussion connecting voices across politics and identities. With Omar Barghouti and activists Jesse Hagopian, Gabriel Schivone, Kanahus Manuel, and moderator Sarah Eltantawi.

Admission is free and open to the public!

Join the Rachel Corrie Foundation and several TESC academic programs for Peace Works 2015: Justice Rising! A gathering of related struggles that will explore systematized oppression and inspire learning and action for local and global justice and peace.
Justice Rising! is cosponsored by The President’s Diversity Fund at The Evergreen State College, Evergreen Students for Justice in Palestine, and the following Evergreen Programs: Power in American Society; Cultural Landscapes; Landscapes of Faith and Power in the Eastern Mediterranean; Political Economy and Social Movements; and What Does it Mean to be an American?
Peace Works is an annual project of The Rachel Corrie Foundation which continues the work that Rachel Corrie began, with her vision, spirit, and creative energy in mind.

Please email Larry Mosqueda, mosqueda@evergreen.edu, for additional information.
room: The Evergreen State College, Olympia, WA - Lecture Hall 1, SEM 2, and Longhouse

title: Opening reception for exhibition of art by Susan Aurand and Lucia Harrison
body:
Nature: Observation, Metaphor, Transformation - Four Decades of Art
Susan Aurand and Lucia Harrison
Opening reception: April 2, 2015, 5-7 pm
Exhibition continues through May 6, 2015

This two-person survey exhibition honors Susan Aurand and Lucia Harrison, artists and teachers who recently retired after decades of teaching at The Evergreen State College. Their influence on students has been profound, and their own art-making practice has flourished.

The art of both artists parallels the changing environments in their personal and professional lives. Susan and Lucia have highly developed observational skills that they began developing at an early age, in very different environments. At Evergreen, when they taught interdisciplinary programs with scientists, they helped others hone these skills, while continuing to build their own.

Susan grew up in the Midwest where her relationship with nature was confined to mostly housing developments. Wild nature roamed in her imagination. Initially Susan concentrated on ceramics, and sculptural elements continue to be important in her artworks. When she came to teach at Evergreen, she gravitated toward two-dimensional art. Her work in drawing, painting and assemblages reflects her interests in mythology and metaphor and her passion for the ever-changing quality of light and color in nature.

Lucia grew up on Cooper Point in Olympia roaming the forests and shores of Puget Sound. Trained as an artist and social scientist, Lucia developed an interest in qualitative research methods, ethnography, and environmental education. While teaching with scientists, she developed a practice of field journaling as inspiration for her paintings, drawings, and artist books. These works reflect her observations of nature and the inspiration she finds there. As nature inspires her, so too her artworks inspire viewers to deepen their own interest in the natural and cultural history of South Puget Sound.

title: You Are Live
body:
You Are Live is a sitcom that will be filmed in front of a live studio audience on April 10th and 11th at 7pm in Evergreen's CCAM Television Studio (Lib 1353). You Are Live hopes to make a statement about the growing support of surveillance and voyeurism in our culture. The performance will incorporate interactive computer programming elements which will utilize the image of any and all audience members, so by attending the event you are automatically authorizing the use of your image during the sitcom itself and in the final product (which will NOT be sold for money, but may be made public on the internet).

Remember: You Are Live whether or not you choose to attend.

body:

title: Generation PsYchedelic Conference
body:
As psychedelics move back to the forefront of medicine and therapy, individuals from Generation Y are stepping up to help push the movement forward. Generation PsYchedelic is a 3-day conference celebrating the younger generation of the psychedelic movement and hopes to create a platform for their voices. We will bring together key players and student speakers within Generation Y who are devoted to integrating psychedelics back into society as therapeutic tools.

Generation PsYchedelic is produced by the Greener’s Association for Psychedelic Studies (GAPS) at the Evergreen State College, in Olympia WA. We meet every Thursday at 4 PM in the Cab Conference Room to discuss how psychedelics relate to topic such as therapy, spirituality, risk reduction, and scientific study.

We will bring together key players and student speakers within Generation Y who are devoted to integrating psychedelics back into society as therapeutic tools.

Generation PsYchedelic is produced by the Greener’s Association for Psychedelic Studies (GAPS) at the Evergreen State College, in Olympia WA. We meet every Thursday at 4 PM in the Cab Conference Room to discuss how psychedelics relate to topic such as therapy, spirituality, risk reduction, and scientific study.

title: Dr. Cornel West Speaks
body:
Cornel West is a prominent and provocative democratic intellectual. He is a Professor of Philosophy and Christian Practice at Union Theological Seminary and Professor Emeritus at Princeton University. He has also taught at Yale, Harvard, and the University of Paris. Cornel West graduated Magna Cum Laude from Harvard in three years and obtained his M.A and Ph.D. in Philosophy at Princeton. He has written over 20 books and has edited 13. Though he is best known for his classics, Race Matters and Democracy Matters, and for his memoir, Brother West: Living and Loving Out Loud, his most recent releases, Black Prophetic Fire and Radical King, were received with critical acclaim.

Doors open at 6:00 pm, and the event starts at 7:00 pm.
Students and Faculty pay $7 in advance, $10 at the door
General Admission $20 in advance, $25 at the door
Tickets available through Rainy Day Records, Greener Store, Tacoma Program, Quality Food Centers (QFC's) and TicketsWest.com, as well as at the door.

This event is sponsored by S&A Productions.

title: Native author Roxanne Dunbar-Ortiz speaks at Longhouse May 5
body:
Native American feminist scholar and activist Roxanne Dunbar-Ortiz will be speaking at the Evergreen Longhouse on Tuesday, May 5, at 7:00 pm, about her new book An Indigenous Peoples' History of the United States, published by Beacon Press.

The publisher describes the book: “Today, in the United States, there are more than five hundred federally recognized indigenous communities and nations comprising nearly three million people. These individuals are the descendants of the once fifteen million people who inhabited this land and are the subject of the latest book by noted historian and activist Roxanne Dunbar-Ortiz. In An Indigenous Peoples’ History of the United States, Dunbar-Ortiz challenges the founding myth of the United States and shows how policy against the indigenous peoples was genocidal and imperialist--designed to crush the original inhabitants. Spanning more than three hundred years, this classic bottom-up history significantly reframes how we view our past. Told from the viewpoint of the indigenous, it reveals how Native Americans, for centuries, actively resisted expansion of the U.S. empire.”

“An Indigenous Peoples’ History of the United States provides an essential historical reference for all Americans. . . . The American Indians’ perspective has been absent from colonial histories for too long, leaving continued misunderstandings of our struggles for sovereignty and human rights.”
--Peterson Zah, former president of the Navajo Nation

“Roxanne Dunbar-Ortiz writes a masterful story that relates what the Indigenous peoples of the United States have always maintained: Against the settler U.S. nation, Indigenous peoples have persevered against actions and policies intended to exterminate them, whether physically, mentally, or intellectually. Indigenous nations and their people continue to bear witness to their experiences under the U.S. and demand justice as well as the realization of sovereignty on their own terms.”
--Jennifer Nez Denetdale, Associate Professor of American Studies at the University of New Mexico and author of Reclaiming Diné History

“An Indigenous Peoples’ History …pulls up the paving stones and lays bare the deep history of the United States, from the corn to the reservations. If the United States is a ‘crime scene,’ as she calls it, then Dunbar-Ortiz is its forensic scientist. A sobering look at a grave history.”
--Vijay Prashad, author of The Poorer Nations

“Justice-seekers everywhere will celebrate Dunbar-Ortiz’s unflinching commitment to truth—a truth that places settler-colonialism and genocide exactly where they belong: as foundational to the existence of the United States.”
--Waziyatawin, PhD, activist and author of For Indigenous Minds Only

More background on the book at h​t​t​p​:​/​/​w​w​w​.​b​e​a​c​o​n​.​o​r​g​/​A​n​-​I​n​d​i​g​e​n​o​u​s​-​P​e​o​p​l​e​s​-​H​i​s​t​o​r​y-of-the-United-States-P1041.aspx

About Roxanne Dunbar-Ortiz

Roxanne Dunbar-Ortiz grew up in rural Oklahoma, daughter of a landless farmer and half-Indian mother. Her paternal grandfather, a white settler, farmer, and veterinarian, had been a labor activist and Socialist in Oklahoma with the Industrial Workers of the World in the first two decades of the twentieth century. The stories of her grandfather inspired her to lifelong social justice activism. Married at eighteen, she left with her husband for San Francisco, California, where she has lived most of the years since, although the marriage ended. Her account of life up to leaving Oklahoma is recorded in Red Dirt: Growing Up Okie. She has a daughter, Michelle.

Roxanne graduated, majoring in History, from San Francisco State College, a working class public institution, but was selected for History graduate school at University of California at Berkeley, transferring to University of California, Los Angeles to complete her doctorate in History. From 1967 to 1972, she was a full time activist living in various parts of the United States, traveling to Europe, Mexico, and Cuba. This time of her life and the aftermath, 1960-1975, is the story told in Outlaw Woman: Memoir of the War Years.

Roxanne took a position teaching in a newly established Native American Studies program at California State University at Hayward, near San Francisco, and helped develop the Department of Ethnic Studies, as well as Women's Studies. In 1974, she became active in the American Indian Movement (AIM) and the International Indian Treaty Council, beginning a lifelong commitment to international human rights.

Her first published book, The Great Sioux Nation: An Oral History of the Sioux Nation and its Struggle for Sovereignty, was published in 1977 and was presented as the fundamental document at the first international conference on Indians of the Americas, held at United Nations' headquarters in Geneva, Switzerland. That book was followed by two others in the following years: Roots of Resistance: A History of Land Tenure in New Mexico, 1680-1980 and Indians of the Americas: Human Rights and Self-Determination. In over a hundred trips to Nicaragua and Honduras from 1981 to 1989, she monitored what was called the Contra War. Her book, Blood on the Border: A Memoir of the Contra War was published in 2005.

More background on the author at http://www.reddirtsite.com

Sponsors

Roxanne Dunbar-Ortiz’s visit is sponsored by the Evergreen program “Native Decolonization in the Pacific Rim: From the Northwest to New Zealand,” in collaboration with the TESC President's Diversity Fund, Longhouse Education and Cultural Center, Native Programs at Evergreen, Olympia Timberland Library, Friends of the Library, Center for Community-Based Learning and Action, TESC Tacoma, & TESC programs “Current Economic & Social Issues,” “Reflecting on Activism,” and “Branching Out: Ethnobotanical Gardens.”
For background on Native Programs at Evergreen: http://www.evergreen.edu/nativeprograms

Directions

The Evergreen State College is located at 2700 Evergreen Parkway NW (the closest parking will be in the B Lot; turn to the left as you drive into campus, and walk the footpath to the Longhouse).

For more information on the event, please contact, or see the following website

https://www.facebook.com/events/1600612936891836/

Zoltan Grossman

title: Film Showing: The Hunting Ground
body:
The Hunting Ground is a documentary film about sexual violence on college campuses in the United States. It was released this year, and follows the stories of college students whose claims of sexual assault weren't taken seriously by their college's administration. The themes of this documentary are salient for college students, and covers some of the recent history of students making challenges to their campus' sexual violence policies and obligations under Title IX.

For more information on the event, please contact, or see the following website

title: POSTPONED: Pinkwashing Exposed: Seattle Fights Back - Queer Week Film Screening
body:
This event has been postponed until next Thursday, same place, same time.

"Pinkwashing" is a term activists have coined for when countries engage in terrible human rights violations promote themselves as "gay friendly" to improve their public image. Israel initiated this strategy as part of a rebranding campaign. Through the inspiring story of these activists' victory, Pinkwashing Exposed explores how pinkwashing works and what local activists are doing to fight back.

The screening is free and will be followed by a facilitated discussion on pinkwashing & homonationalism.

Brought to you as part of Queer Week by student organizations Queer and Trans* People of Color (QTPOC) and Students for Justice in Palestine (SJP).

If accommodation is required for this event, please contact Student Activities with reasonable advance notice by emailing StudentActivities@evergreen.edu or by calling 360-867-6220 or 360-867-6834(TTY).

title: PLATO Lecture Series
body:
PLATO Lecture Series 2015 (Intended audience: students, faculty, staff, community members)

Computer-aided Environmental Science; Fridays 12-1 pm in Lecture Hall 1
" Sensitivity of aquatic leaf litter breakdown to global changes"
Friday May 29, 2015: Dr. Jennifer Follstad Shah from Environmental & Sustainability Studies, University of Utah

The response of leaf litter breakdown to elevated temperature in streams and rivers worldwide is uncertain given variation in macroinvertebrate responses to temperature, large differences in plant litter quality, and nutrient enrichment of streams and rivers. A recent synthesis shows that the global apparent temperature sensitivity of leaf litter breakdown in unpolluted streams and rivers was 0.34 ± 0.04 eV, which was lower than the value predicted by metabolic theory (~0.60 eV). We propose that lower than expected values may reflect ecoenzyme activity as a rate limiting step in the decay process or thermal adaptation my microbes and macroinvertebrates. We estimate that rates may increase by 11-16% with a 2-3 °C average global increase in water temperature, but the balance of microbial and metazoan contributions to leaf litter processing is unlikely to change. Hypotheses and conceptual figures regarding expected effects of elevated nutrients on the temperature sensitivity of leaf litter breakdown will be presented as fodder for an open exchange of ideas. To learn more about Dr. Shah’s research, please visit her website:
http://follstadshah.weebly.com/

For more information on the event, email leroyc@evergreen.edu.
room: The Evergreen State College, Olympia, WA - Lecture Hall 1
repeat: Friday, May 29, 2015 - 12:00 pm to 1:00 pm

title: Bush Farm Archaeology Dig Information Session
body:
This summer, the first Evergreen-run archaeological field school will be conducted at the George Bush Homestead, the mid-19th-century property of African-American George Bush, his German-American wife Isabella, and their children, located in what is today Tumwater. This family was one of the first settler families in the greater Olympia area, and helped build some of the earliest industry. This project hopes to raise awareness of this under-reported, but integral, piece of early settlement history of our state.

We would like to invite any interested parties, including the public as well as the Evergreen community, to an information and input meeting this Thursday. We will be describing the project's parameters, methods, and dissemination, as well as publicizing the dates for public tours on the site. If you have any questions or input for the project, including research questions and design, we welcome your suggestions and comments. The meeting will not follow a time schedule, so drop in any time.

For more information on the event, please contact, or see the following website

blogs.evergreen.edu/bushhomestead/

title: The Tanoak Tree Book Talk
body:
Author, botanist and Evergreen professor Frederica Bowcutt will discuss her new book The Tanoak Tree: An Environmental History of a Pacific Coast Hardwood. Tanoak is a resilient and common hardwood tree native to California and southwestern Oregon. People's radically different perceptions of it have ranged from treasured food plant to cash crop to trash tree. Today tanoaks are experiencing massive die-offs due to sudden oak death, an introduced disease. Having studied the patterns of tanoak use and abuse for nearly twenty years, botanist Frederica Bowcutt uncovers a complex history of cultural, sociopolitical, and economic factors affecting the tree's fate.

http://www.orcabooks.com/event/saturday-september-26th-300pm-frederica-b...
room: Orca Books, 509 4th Ave E, Olympia, WA 98501, United States

title: The Aids Memorial Quilt on display
body:
Showing Oct. 1-31, 2015

The Library, in partnership with the Tacoma Art Museum, is proud to present panels from The AIDS Memorial Quilt, on display in the library through the month of October.

The Quilt panels are hung above the landing between our second and third floors.

This remarkable memorial project began in San Francisco in 1986 when Cleve Jones founded The NAMES Project and stitched the first panel in memory of his friend Marvin Feldman.

Those of us who remember San Francisco in the 1980s remember Jones's determination that the people who died from AIDS would not be forgotten, even as we had to organize ground up, community by community, to support each other against this disease. The NAMES Project is one of many examples of the ways we were thinking in an emergency.

Today The Quilt includes more than 48,000 individual panels. It is the largest community art project in the world and continues to be a vital gathering point for collective mourning and for HIV/AIDS education.

Please visit the Library during October and spend time with the eight panels we are hosting.

Viewing The Quilt provides many opportunities for our campus to support each other as we mourn loved ones we have lost, to learn about HIV/AIDS in history and today (35 million people live with HIV/AIDS worldwide), and to renew commitments to HIV education and prevention.

Today in this country 1 infection in 4 occurs in youth aged 13-24. Most do not know they carry HIV are are not being treated.

For viewing opportunities, please check our library hours http://www.evergreen.edu/library/hours.htm.

For more information on the event, please contact, or see the following website
http://www.aidsquilt.org/about

title: Shellfish Club Work Party
body:
The Shellfish Club sponsors bi-monthly work parties year-round at the the Evergreen Shellfish garden. During the Fall and Winter, work parties are held at varying times at night; during the Spring and Summer, work parties are held at varying times during the day. Events are open to any member of the Evergreen community. The Shellfish Club supports safe access by supplying boots, gloves, and headlamps (supplies limited).

Before accessing the garden, a safety and best-practices talk is given to all participants. All work on the garden is supervised. In the case of an emergency, we provide access to a first aid kit and also have close proximity to an emergency beacon at the Geoduck House parking lot. The Shellfish Club coordinators, as standard practice, always: notify the caretaker of the Geoduck House that we will be accessing the garden, call Department of Health to check water quality, and provide hands-on education and guidance to all participants.

title: Frederica Bowcutt: The Tanoak Tree
body: Author, botanist and Evergreen professor Frederica Bowcutt will discuss her new book The Tanoak Tree: An Environmental History of a Pacific Coast Hardwood. Tanoak is a resilient and common hardwood tree native to California and southwestern Oregon. People's radically different perceptions of it have ranged from treasured food plant to cash crop to trash tree. Today tanoaks are experiencing massive die-offs due to sudden oak death, an introduced disease. Having studied the patterns of tanoak use and abuse for nearly twenty years, botanist Frederica Bowcutt uncovers a complex history of cultural, sociopolitical, and economic factors affecting the tree's fate.
room: Washington State Capitol Museum Coach House, Olympia, WA
repeat: Monday, October 12, 2015 - 7:00 pm to 8:00 pm

title: African Art and Art History
body:
Pam McClusky, the curator of the Seattle Art Museum, will lecture on African art and art history in the context of world art history. Her lecture will speak to colonial history in Africa, local resistance and the role of art collections in peace and in times of war. Her talk will enhance our understanding of models of navigating in emergencies.

When world art history is studied, African art is often marginalized in the narrative and colonial history and its role in art collection, which committed social injustices in countless cases, are often omitted. McClusky will address both issues, putting African art in the context of world art history and examining colonial history's role in African art and art collection.

Her lecture may help our learning community to be aware problems in cross-cultural equity and social justice.

Her lecture is part of the Tacoma Speaker’s Series and is financially supported by The President's Diversity Fund and Evergreen’s Tacoma program.

title: VIETNAM-FULL DISCLOSURE: NO MORE LIES-THEN OR NOW
body:
Wednesday, October 21, 2105, Seminar 2, A1105, 1-3PM
“Hearts and Minds” A 1974 Academy Award winning documentary on the History of The Vietnam War and its impact on Vietnam and the US.
Discussion lead by veterans after the movie.

This is a preliminary movie for a
VIETNAM-FULL DISCLOSURE: NO MORE LIES-THEN OR NOW
Teach-In on Wednesday October 28, "Vietnam-Full Disclosure: No More Lies-Then or Now" on the history of the Vietnam Era and why it is still important. That event will be held on:
VIETNAM-FULL DISCLOSURE: NO MORE LIES-THEN OR NOW
Teach-In on Wednesday October 28, "Vietnam-Full Disclosure: No More Lies-Then or Now" on the history of the Vietnam Era and why it is still important.
The Speakers at that event will be:
* Mark Fleming, Veterans for Peace organizer on the history of American Intervention in Vietnam
* Anh-Tri Nguyen, Vietnamese Student in the US in the 1970s and currently living in the US
* Graham Clumpner, Veteran from Iraq Veterans Against the War,
* Larry Kershner, Vietnam V4P activist and Poetry
* Peter Bohmer, TESC faculty on the Anti-war movement in the US
* Glen Anderson, of the Fellowship of Reconciliation on the cost of the war

Why these events and why now?
The USG, through the Pentagon is having a 50-year Commemoration to rewrite the history of the Vietnam War era. (See http://www.vietnamwar50th.com/) .
There is a concerted effort to make the US government actions in the war honorable and to glorify war, which is a disservice to those who lost their lives in the war (both the Vietnamese and the US soldiers) and just as importantly, the lives that are being lost and will continue to be lost in current and future wars. Veterans for Peace at the national and local level are involved in this effort to set the record straight. See their website of Vietnam Full Disclosure- http://vietnamfulldisclosure.org/
Sponsored by Academic programs “Political Economy of Power in American Society,” “Caliban and the Witch,” “Culture and Violence,” the President’s Diversity Fund and the Olympia Rachel Corrie Chapter 109 of Veterans for Peace. All events are free and open to students and the community. Parking on campus is available for $2. For more information contact Larry Mosqueda at 360-867-6513 or mosqueda@evergreen.edu or Mark Fleming at 360-357-1060 or rezdog02@hotmail.com.

For more information contact Larry Mosqueda at 360-867-6513

The event is FREE and open to the public, so bring the whole family and spend the day browsing artisan vendors and learning from an array of workshops. Also sample and enjoy great local food, live music, oyster shucking competitions, FREE pumpkin carving, cider pressing, and a raffle with the chance to win a Sundog CSA share.

title: VIETNAM - FULL DISCLOSURE: NO MORE LIES, THEN OR NOW
body:
"Vietnam - Full Disclosure: No More Lies, Then or Now", is a Teach-In on the history of the Vietnam Era and why it is still important. This event is conducted as the US government, through the Pentagon, uses a 50-year Commemoration to rewrite the history of the Vietnam War era (see http://www.vietnamwar50th.com/), defining US actions as honorable and glorifying war. Contrarily, national and local Veterans for Peace, calling the commemoration a disservice to the soldiers and civilians who lost their lives in the war, intend to set the record straight. Sponsored by Academic programs “Political Economy of Power in American Society”, “Caliban and the Witch”, “Culture and Violence”, and the Olympia Rachel Corrie Chapter 109 of Veterans for Peace.

Preceding the event, as background for the Teach-In, catch these two films: “Hearts and Minds”, a 1974 Academy Award winning documentary on the history of the war and its impact on Vietnam and the US (Oct. 21, 1-3 p.m., Sem. 2, A1105); and “Sir! No Sir!", a 2005 award winning film on the GI movement against the Vietnam War in both the US and Vietnam (Oct. 23, 1-3 p.m., Sem. 2, B1105).

For more information on the event see the following website
http://vietnamfulldisclosure.org/

body:
Peace Corps service is a life-defining leadership experience. Since 1961, the Peace Corps has shared with the world America's most precious resource – its people. Volunteers serve in over 60 countries in Africa, Asia, the Caribbean, Central and South America, Europe, the Pacific Islands and the Middle East. You can make a difference for 27 months in a developing community overseas with a job in Education, Health, Environment, Agriculture, Youth Development, or Community Economic Development. title: Indigenous Climate Justice Symposium
body:
The 1st annual Indigenous Climate Justice Symposium will be held at The Evergreen State College Longhouse on November 5-6, 2015. It will bring together speakers from Native communities that are working to keep fossil fuels in the ground, by stopping coal terminals, oil trains and fracking, and protecting treaty resources from the threat of climate change. Its major goal would be to get students and youth, particularly tribal youth, involved in community-based climate justice efforts. All events are free and open to Evergreen students and the public (please inform the organizers about any classes that may attend).

--

THURSDAY, NOVEMBER 5:

STUDENT RESEARCH DAY
(10:00 am – 5:00 pm)
Students can send a 150-word abstract proposal for a 15-20-minute presentation to wynns@evergreen.edu by Sunday, October 25.

KEYNOTE BY TOM GOLDTOOTH
(7:00 – 9:30 pm)
Indigenous Environmental Network Executive Director:
“The Paris Climate Accord: Will it be a Crime Against Humanity and Mother Earth?”
http://www.ienearth.org

__________

The Symposium is an outgrowth of the Climate Change and Pacific Rim Indigenous Nations Project at Evergreen, started by the Northwest Indian Applied Research Institute. The Project published a 2006 report for Indigenous leadership, a 2010 community organizing booklet, and the 2012 Oregon State University Press anthology "Asserting Native Resilience: Pacific Rim Indigenous Nations Face the Climate Crisis." For these publications, see http://academic.evergreen.edu/g/grossmaz/climate.html

Symposium sponsored by the Climate Change and Pacific Rim Indigenous Nations Project, and hosted by the Resource Rebels program, with support from the Graduate Program on the Environment, Master of Public Administration – Tribal Governance, Native Programs and Sustainability & Justice planning units, President’s Diversity Fund, Clean Energy Committee, Academic Deans’ Office, and Evergreen programs Engaging with Endangered Northwest, Shipping Out & Writing Home, Caliban & the Witch, Even When Erased We Exist, and Introduction to Environmental Studies.

title: Pollinating Rios Vivos with The Beehive Design Collective
body:
Hosted by the student organization Black Cottonwood Collective.

(abajo en español)

The Bees will be at Evergreen with their giant, portable murals! Beehive collective´s graphics aim to draw-out the connections between colonial history and present day struggles against corporate globalization, violence, and racism. The Beehive creates anti-copyright graphics as tools for popular analysis, education, and organizing. Our presentations and workshops offer an accessible format for unpacking the ways in which resource extraction, militarization, and industrial development in the Western Hemisphere are all interconnected in the same 'big picture.'

Once again, this fall a visiting Bee from the Polinizaciones project in Abya Yala (South America), who is also a member of the Ríos Vivos Movement in Colombia, is heading out on tour to the Pacific Coast of Turtle Island (North America) and then onto the Florida pensinsula (southeast US). This collaborative tour will share stories from Ríos Vivos Colombia, the social movement of dam impacted communities that struggle for the defense of their territories and rivers, and for an energy model by and for the people, and also the work of Polinizaciones, a Beehive grassroots process that collaborates with communities impacted by resource extraction in the use of arts, culture, and communications as strategies for land defense in Colombia, Ecuador, and Venezuela.

Using Beehive graphics and other culture and communications work, Polinizaciones creates another way to learn, create, and understand our history in the context of globalization and free trade, militarization, the war on drugs, and the infrastructure and extraction projects integral to IIRSA-Project Mesoamérica. The Polinizaciones sharing session will highlight the Beehive's giant banners, accompanied by photographs, short films, personal experiences, and stories about the communities in resistance we have been weaving relationships of mutual aid with over the last eight years.

Throughout Abya Yala, Beehive graphics are being used by youth and community educators within Native, Afro descendent, rural, and urban poor communities as a medium for dialogue and raising consciousness around the current threats against these communities. The Ríos Vivos Movement in Colombia is just one process that has appropriated Beehive collective graphics as part of their movement.

-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

el Colectivo de Diseño la Colmena y el Movimiento Ríos Vivos-Colombia presenta la

Polinizando Ríos Vivos: Gira de la Costa Pacifica y la Península de Florida!
octubre- diciembre 2015

La Abejas regresan a Evergreen con sus murales portátiles gigantes! Las Abejas ilustran las conexiones entre la historia colonial y las realidades actuales de las luchas contra la globalización neoliberal, la violencia y el racismo. La Colmena, crea obras gráficas sin derechos de autor que se usan como herramientas para promover el análisis, la educación y la organización popular. Las presentaciones y talleres están hechos en un formato accesible para poder entender mejor la extracción de los recursos naturales, la militarización y el desarrollo industrial en América, sus interconexiones y su vínculo con procesos mucho más grandes.

Nuevamente, este otoño una abeja del proyecto Polinizaciones en Abya Yala (Suramérica), que también es integrante del Movimiento Ríos Vivos Colombia, realizará una gira por la Costa Pacifica de Isla Tortuga (Norteamérica) y la Península de Florida (sureste estadounidense). Esta gira colaborativa va compartir historias del Movimiento Ríos Vivos, el movimiento social de las comunidades impactadas por represas en Colombia y que luchan por la defensa de sus territorios y ríos, y por un modelo energético de y para los, y también el trabajo de Polinizaciones, un proceso popular de la Colmena que colabora con comunidades impactadas por la extracción de recursos con el uso del arte, cultura y comunicación como estrategias por la defensa del Territorio.

Usando las obras de la Colmena además de otros medios culturales y comunicativos, Polinizaciones crea otras maneras de aprender, crear y también entender nuestras historias dentro de los contextos de la globalización y el libre comercio, la militarización y la Guerra en contra el narcotráfico, y los proyectos de infraestructura y de extracción de recursos naturales al IIRSA- Proyecto Mesoamérica. Este compartir con Polinizaciones tendrá presenta los telones grandes de la Colmena, y también fotos, videos cortos, experiencias propias e historias de las comunidades en resistencia con quien hemos estado tejiendo relaciones de apoyo mutuo durante los últimos ocho años.

Por toda Abya Yala, las obras gráficas de la Colmena están siendo utilizadas por jóvenes y docentes de comunidades indígenas, afro descendientes, campesinos y urbanos populares como un medio para crear dialogo y conciencia de las amenazas que enfrentan. El Movimiento Ríos Vivos Colombia es apenas un espacio donde se ha apropiado los gráficos de la Colmena como parte de su proceso.

title: Fillmmaker, Jesse Freeston, to show Resistencia
body:
Join Film-maker Jesse Freeston for a Film Screening: "Resistencia: The Fight for the Aguan Valley"
No Charge

TRAILER: resistenciathefilm.com/trailer

The film: Resistencia: The Fight for the Aguan Valley
June 28th, 2009. The Honduran people are preparing to vote in the first referendum in the country's history. The proposition is to write a new constitution, and a 'yes' vote could dramatically transform the country, perhaps even guaranteeing land for the country's 300,000 landless farmers. But, instead of waking up to ballot boxes, they see soldiers carrying out the first coup d'état in Central America in three decades. This is the story of the two thousand farming families who challenged the coup project by taking over the plantations of the most powerful man in the country. The camera follows three members of the movement, and one clever journalist who travels in from the capital city, as they convert the plantations into cooperatives and install locally the democracy they dreamed of seeing nationally. Shot over four years, the film is both a testament to the capacity of an organized movement to transform the most fertile land in the country, as well as an account of the coup regime's violent attempt to get the land back.

The filmmaker: Jesse Freeston is an independiente documentary filmmaker and video-journalist based in Montréal, Québec. Jesse has worked with The Real News Network, teleSUR, Al Jazeera, CUTV, and Vice. He has completed two independent documentaries, the first entitled Revolutionary Medicine: A Story of the First Garifuna Hospital (co-directed by Beth Geglia) and in 2015 he released his first feature-length documentary, Resistencia: The Fight for the Aguan Valley.

For more information on the event, please see the following website
resistenciathefilm.com/trailer

NBC embarks on its latest musical holiday tradition: a 3-hour LIVE event production of the groundbreaking Broadway show that brought Oz to life in a funky sing-along journey down the yellow brick road.

Now, a Tony-winning creative team, the imaginative Cirque du Soleil Theatrical and a diverse cast of showstoppers create an eye-popping new take unlike anything ever seen.

From Executive Producers Craig Zadan and Neil Meron comes an adventure of stunning spectacle and toe-tapping music.

title: Prison Obscura opens, Evergreen Gallery's winter show
body:
This exhibit of photographs invites us to question "the dominant narratives and stereotypes that somehow justify a U.S. system now locking up people at an unprecedented rate. What do we know of our prisons? Do photographs help us know? Are the images of prisons we see reliable? Are they even useful? How do images relate to the political, social, and economic realities that exist within our prison industrial complex? Do prisons, as closed sites, present any challenges to the claims photography makes as a medium of communication?" -- Curated by Pete Brook. Open to the entire community.

For more information on the event, please see the following website
https://sites.evergreen.edu/gallery/event/prison-obscura/

title: {DUALITY, DESTRUCTION & DESIRE} Live Dance Performance
body:
DUALITY, DESTRUCTION & DESIRE
a dance theater performance
presented by the Evergreen Embodied Arts Tribe

ONE NIGHT ONLY, Friday, February 5th
@ EXPERIMENTAL THEATRE in the Communications (COMM) building

7:30pm - doors open | 8:00pm - performance begins
$5 suggested donation for students

Incorporating elements of Japanese BUTOH dance, German Expressionist Theater, multimedia and performance art, this performance addresses the loss of innocent lives in Iraq and Afghanistan from American bombs and drones, in hopes of inspiring a new generation of people to work for peace and nonviolence for all of humanity. You are invited to experience a powerful performance journey intended to provoke inquiry, communicate knowledge, inspire understanding and transform our collective consciousness.

For more information on the event, please see the following website
https://www.facebook.com/groups/embodiedartstribe/

title: Geoduck Gallop Half Marathon and 10k
body:
Description *
The original Geoduck Gallop was established in 1984, but only lasted through the following year. Formerly a pledge run/walk, in 2006 it was re-invented as a Half Marathon and a 10k road run/walk. The race was set up as a qualifying course for Evergreen Track and Field Team members wishing to run the standard for the NAIA National Championships Marathon and opened to the public.

The course starts and finishes in front of the Costantino Recreation Center and takes runners onto the rural roads and bike paths surrounding the campus and follows wide shoulders the majority of the race. The course will be well marked (including mile markers), monitored at intersections, and will have water stations at various points. To reduce encounters with the already minimal car traffic, there will be an out-and-back section in the last four miles of the course.

This is a USATF certified course.

For more information on the event, please see the following website
http://www.evergreen.edu/recreation/roadraces/gallop.htm

title: Art Lecture Series: Melissa Buzzeo
body:
Evergreen Art Lecture Series presents a broad range of interdisciplinary approaches to contemporary art issues by artists, writers, activists and scholars. The emphasis is to introduce the way in which a variety of practices undertake fields of inquiry in the arts. The series provides a lively forum for the exchange of ideas between the speakers, students, faculty and the public.

Melissa Buzzeo is a Brooklyn based poet. She writes a literature of encounter, but also: descent, healing, refusal. She is the author of four full-length books: The Devastation (Nightboat 2015), For Want and Sound (Les Figues, 2013), Face (Bookthug, 2009) and What Began Us (Leon Works, 2007). She teaches creative writing at Pratt Institute in Brooklyn and maintains a radical palm reading practice. At one time, she went to Cornell and then to Iowa. Currently she is working on a specific kind of memoir simply called Writing.

title: Dana Lyons Songwriter and Activist
body:
Famous northwest songwriter and activist, Dana Lyons, is coming to speak and perform in the program Engaging with the Endangered Northwest! He will share his hit songs and talk about his work as as an artist and activist, and how he has worked on coal, oil, and energy issues, issues related to the forests and waters of the great Salish Sea, work on unions, sustainability and justice, work with Jane Goodall, and other topics. He will share hits such as "Cows with Guns," "Drop of Water,” and other favorites.

Dana is one of the great songwriters, activists, poets, and bio-regional bards of our age. We are very fortunate that Dana had an opening in his schedule, and that he has agreed to come to Olympia and at Evergreen on Leap Year Day.

For more information on the event, please see the following website
https://www.cowswithguns.com/

title: Andrew Culp: "Politics in the Age of Environmental Thinking”
body:
From Andrew Culp: "What happens to the concept of 'politics' when ecological crises become the leading threat to our way of life? Or more provocatively, what happens when governance 'no longer confronts us like a subject facing us, but an environment that is hostile to us'? In this talk, I discuss how the traditional concept of politics as conflict is reconfigured by the ecological milieu, a diffusion of complex forces, and non-human actors."

Andrew Culp is a Visiting Assistant Professor of Rhetoric Studies at Whitman College. His work is on the cultural study of new paradigms of power. He recently completed a manuscript, Dark Deleuze and the Death of This World, and his work has appeared in Angelaki: Journal of the Theoretical Humanities, Communication and Critical/Cultural Studies, parallax, Radical Philosophy, and Affinities: A Journal of Radical Theory, Culture, and Action. This will be the final Winter Quarter lecture in the Anthropocene Consortium Lecture Series.

For more information on the event, please see the following website
sites.evergreen.edu/anthropocene

title: Anti-Bias Childrearing
body:
With support from the President's Diversity Fund, the Children's Center is sponsoring parent educator and Evergreen graduate Candyce Lund Bollinger for a workshop on Anti-bias Child-rearing. “Anti-bias” means to actively teach children to identify, question, and work to change biases such as racism, sexism, ableism, homophobia, and classism, and to do so in age-appropriate ways.

Please join us in learning how to bring anti-bias tenets and practice into our interactions with children and each other. Coffee has generously been provided by the Office of Student Affairs.

title: All ages cultural Canoe Race paddle for fun. Free for everyone!
body:
Canoe at Evergreen beach Sunday, March 13th at 2 p.m.
I am bringing one or two large Native American canoes to Evergreen beach Sunday, March 13th at 2 p.m. I would like to have people that are taller than me to help load the canoes Saturday night around 5:30 p.m. in Oakville (Great Wolf Lodge or Lucky Eagle I-5 exit). Please let me know if you are able to help with either one. Remember everyone is welcome, ages 5 on up, any culture or race. I hope you can even come if only to watch. We will supply life jackets and paddles, it is suggested to bring a change of clothes because we will be so close to the water.

This is an awesome opportunity to be a part of history and to learn more about this awesome culture!

Theresa Shortman
360-388-8737

title: Power Dialog
body:
In the battle against climate change Washington DC may be in gridlock, but Washington State is in the HOV lane. Come to The Evergreen State College in Olympia to meet with state officials who are helping to guide carbon policy, hear about their plans first hand, and ask hard questions about how far the state can go toward decarbonizing our economy. Find out what impact these policies will have on economic inequality and social justice.

This event is part of the national Power Dialog program designed by Bard College's Center for Environmental Policy, and meetings like this one will be taking place in nearly all states. The goal is to raise awareness about policies to reduce carbon emissions that are going forward, even in the face of obstruction at the federal level. It’s also a chance for your voice to be heard—for you to let public officials know what you think needs to be done to preserve a liveable planet.

Washington State’s Power Dialog will take place on April 4, 1:00 – 3:00 pm in the Recital Hall of the Communication Arts building. On hand will be Sarah Rees from the Department of Ecology and Tony Usibelli from the Department of Commerce—and students from colleges and universities around the state. Join us!

Here is the plan:

1. Prepare for the Dialog. Learn about the Clean Power Plan—the Obama proposal to prod the states into reducing carbon emissions in electricity generation—and Washington State’s planning for pricing carbon and cutting back on fossil fuels. Debate whether these plans go far enough and in the right direction.

2. Select a representative to be on stage with the state officials, and prepare a question that expresses the interest of the whole class. We will give all these questions a chance to be voiced and then open the floor to all students who have come for the Dialog.

3. Let us know you’re coming. Contact Peter Dorman (dormanp@evergreen.edu), a faculty member with the Master of Environmental Studies degree at The Evergreen State College, if you have any additonal questions. We’re here to help you with any logistical problems you may have.

For more information on the event, please see the following website
http://www.evergreen.edu/mes/powerdialog

body:

title: Critical Trans Politics and the Limits of Law
body:
Dean Spade, Professor at Seattle University Law School and founder of the Sylvia Rivera Law Project, offers a presentation on what law can and cannot offer political movements in support of transgender people. Author of the ground breaking book Normal Life, Dean Spade brings intersectional analysis to trans studies and trans politics, including with work on the security state, racism, and the prison industrial complex. Audience: students, staff, faculty, and the community.

For more information on the event, please see the following website
http://www.deanspade.net/

title: Mexico: Government Repression Grows Against Indigenous Self-Defense Forces
body:
This panel will focus primarily on exploring the politicized incarceration of Nestora Salgado, neoliberalism, and the drug war in Mexico as well as touch on indigenous, feminist, and ecological justice movements in Mexico.

Nestora Salgado is an indigenous leader, a naturalized U.S. citizen and ex-political prisoner in Mexico. She was seized without an arrest warrant by Mexican federal soldiers in August 2013 as a result of her leadership role in community policing against organized crime. Salgado was transferred to a maximum security prison far away from her home community of Olinalá and held incommunicado for over 30 months.

Dr. Filiberto Barajas- López, Professor at the U.W. College of education, will discuss the autodefensa movement and its roots in the community-based tradition of self-government in Michoacán, where Dr. López’s family has lived for generations.

Su Docekal, chair of the Freedom for Nestora committee in Seattle, will discuss the international movement to free Salgado, and the legal implications of her case, and will examine the role of U.S. military aid in the repression of indigenous uprisings in Mexico and their efforts to stop international mining companies.

Jair Ramirez, organizer with the Freedom for Nestora committee will be speaking about social movements in Mexico revolving around current events.
sponsor: Freedom for Nestora Libertad Para Nestora

body:
The first of four great events on April 22 and 23 to celebrate Evergreen’s past, present and future; mark the inauguration of President George Bridges; learn about the successes of notable and interesting alumni; spark our thinking about the future of education; and put our values into action with a fun day of community service.

At 1 p.m. be part of history at the inauguration of Evergreen’s sixth president. Experience the installation ceremony and listen to President Bridges’ ideas for “Our College, Our Future.” Special guest speakers include Evergreen's second president and former Washington governor Dan Evans, and philanthropist/entrepreneur and chair of Evergreen’s board of trustees Fred Goldberg. Reception following.

And stick around in the CRC for the Alumni Showcase from 3-5 p.m. (see separate listing). Check out this and other inauguration events at www.evergreen.edu/inauguration.

If you plan to attend any of these events, please RSVP https://forms.evergreen.edu/inauguration-rsvp as soon as possible. Volunteers are also needed. Contact Matt Noonan to volunteer: noonanm@evergreen.edu

title: Most Likely to Succeed film and discussion, Inauguration Event
body:
This is a must-see film for anyone interested in education and one of only two screenings in Washington. The film highlights a model, much like Evergreen’s, that could transform high school education. “The current educational system in the United States was developed a century ago during the rise of the industrial age and was once the envy of the world. However, the world economy has since transformed profoundly, but the US education system has not.” - IMBD. Followed by a discussion with the film's Executive Producer, Ted Dintersmith, Lynda Weinman '76 of lynda.com and Wayne Au, '94, MiT '96 of UW. See the trailer: www.mltsfilm.org.

Check out this and other inauguration events at www.evergreen.edu/inauguration. If you plan to attend any of these events, please RSVP as soon as possible. Volunteers are also needed. Contact Matt Noonan to volunteer: noonanm@evergreen.edu

title: Day of Service, Inauguration Event
body:
Fan out across our area and assist three terrific nonprofits: Capitol Land Trust, Thurston County Food Bank School Gardens and OlyEcosystems (Olympia Coalition for Ecosystem Preservation) with trail maintenance, gardening, and blue heron habitat preservation. Spot President Bridges pitching in at project worksites throughout the day. Part of "Our College, Our Future" inauguration festivities. Includes lunch and transportation.

Check out this and other inauguration events at www.evergreen.edu/inauguration. If you plan to attend any of these events, please RSVP as soon as possible (including volunteering for Day of Service).

Volunteers are also needed for the other inauguration events. Contact Matt Noonan to volunteer for other events: noonanm@evergreen.edu

For more information on the event, please contact, or see the following website
www.evergreen.edu/inauguration/
room: Meet in the Library lobby before heading out to worksites

title: Shellfish Club Work Party
body:
The Shellfish Club meets at the F Lot trail head every other week and provides boots, headlamps, gloves, and rain gear (if needed) to Evergreen students staff, or faculty interested in experiencing the Evergreen Shellfish Garden. They walk through the woods to the north end of the beach, get a tour of the Shellfish Garden and a basic overview of shellfish aquaculture, then do shellfish plot maintenance before learning how to properly (and safely) shuck and eat oysters.

If accommodation is required for this event, please contact Student Activities with reasonable advance notice by emailing StudentActivities@evergreen.edu or by calling 360-867-6220 or 360-867-6834 (TTY).

(the original date was changed to the current date for this event)

title: Self Care and Healing Plants with Survivors and Allies
body:
Day 2 of Sexual Violence Awareness Week

In this workshop, we will talk about connecting to plants, farming and the seasons as one form of self care and healing. We will participate in some farm work and use our bodies to connect to the land, as well as try some herbal medicines and talk about local medicinal plants. If there’s room, we can have some time to individually connect to the GRuB land with a writing activity. Wear something you are willing to get a little dirty on the farm in.

Accessibility: There is a ramp to the GRuB farm house, and fairly flat wood-chipped paths on the farm. Non-gendered individual bathrooms. Bring your questions. CASV's SafePlace trained advocates will be present for support.

Check out other events for SVAW presented by the Coalition Against Sexual Violence  https://www.facebook.com/events/1553100851382516/

title: Dr. Laura Brown: Healthy Relationships After Childhood Trauma
body:
The Women's Resource Center is sponsoring a lecture on healthy relationships after childhood trauma. Dr. Laura Brown will talk about experiences of people who were abused, neglected, or otherwise given less than adequate attachment, love, and connection and as a result struggle in very predictable ways in their adult friendships, work relationships, and romantic relationships. She talks about psychological safety, self-respect, and boundaries for survivors.

If accommodation is required for this event, please contact Student Activities with reasonable advance notice by emailing StudentActivities@evergreen.edu or by calling 360-867-6220 or 360-867-6834(TTY).

title: Shellfish Club Work Party
body:
The Shellfish Club meets at the F Lot trail head every other week and provides boots, headlamps, gloves, and rain gear (if needed) to Evergreen students staff, or faculty interested in experiencing the Evergreen Shellfish Garden. They walk through the woods to the north end of the beach, get a tour of the Shellfish Garden and a basic overview of shellfish aquaculture, then do shellfish plot maintenance before learning how to properly (and safely) shuck and eat oysters.

title: The Next System Teach In
body:
We need a new system! The systems that govern our economy, environment and social justice are not creating the world we want. These systems are not broken, they are working the way someone wants them to. Join us in creating the next system.
RSVP and agenda can be found at http://teachins.thenextsystem.org/evergreen_state
Topics will include:

Emergency Services for Houseless Neighbors

The Power of Peer Support in Mental Health Services

Economic Empowerment Initiative for Women

Public Policy Through the Lens of Compassion

Participatory socialism: A Realistic Utopia

Reducing Greenhouse gases in Thurston County

A World Worth Working In: Sustainable employment practices for the next century

Sustainable Forestry

So Much More

title: Object / Lessons : Thinking Through Craft at The Evergreen State College
body:
In this exhibition at The Evergreeen Gallery students from the 2015-16 Thinking Through Craft program present their work.

Work in metal and wood deal with issues of function, structure, finish, and ornament, but can just as readily address issues such as power, personal space, privileged resources, the uses of discomfort, and the limits of utility. In an intensive year-long program, the members of Thinking Through Craft incorporated a philosophical study of craft with a studio practice. Members of this learning community came with a diverse range of experience, and developed skills in one material over the entire year. The program has culminated in Object/Lessons, an exhibition illuminating our intellectual and creative exploration, and showing our best work. In it, we explore craft through the lenses of Material, Process, Function, Mediation, and Agency.

title: Parking Rate Change Hearing
body:
Parking Rate Change Hearing, Tuesday, May 24, two options available:

  • Option 1: 12-1pm, Library 1005
  • Option 2: 5-6pm, Library 1005

Parking Services is an auxiliary function of the college (not covered in the base budget) and is required to be financially self-sustaining. In recent years Parking Services has not generated enough revenue to meet expenses. The result is that a substantial amount of parking lot maintenance—including preventive maintenance that heads off future damage—has been deferred and funds have not been available to adopt technology to better serve users.   Due primarily to concerns about raising fees during a period of steep tuition increases and flat wages (which was the case in 2010, 2011, 2012 and 2013) parking permit and fine rates have not increased since fall of 2007 (and prior to that, not since 2000). In the meantime, parking-related costs and needs have increased and revenue has continued to fall short.

These modest increases (approximately $.13-.18/day for permits) are projected to provide the necessary revenue through 2020 to address preservation of existing customer service, deferred lot maintenance, and investments in technology to better serve users.

Examples of proposed fee changes:

  • A daily pass is currently $2 and it would increase to $3.
  • A quarterly permit is currently $40 and it would increase to $50.
  • An annual permit is currently $120 and it would increase to $150.

For more information on changes to rates, please see these related links:

  • Parking Services Review DTF Final Report and Appendix 1, Appendix 2, and VPSA response.
  • See earlier response from Wendy Endress, the Vice President for Student Affairs on Greener Commons.

 

If you are unable to attend, please send comments to corna@evergreen.edu no later than noon on Wednesday, May 25 to participate.
sponsor: Office of the Vice President for Student Affairs

title: Post Traumatic Slave Syndrome
body:
The theory of Post Traumatic Slave Syndrome suggest that centuries of slavery followed by systemic racism and oppression have resulted in multigenerational adaptive behaviors―some of which have been positive and reflective of resilience, and others that are detrimental and destructive.

In brief, Dr. Joy DeGruy presents facts, statistics and documents that illustrate how varying levels of both clinically induced and socially learned residual stress‐related issues were passed along through the generations as a result of slavery.
sponsor: Health and Counseling Center, Gateways, Women's Resource Center, Student Activities

title: Dr. Joy DeGruy Healing Workshop
body: Healing begins by simply telling the truth. Dr. Joy believes that “truthfulness is the foundation of all human virtue.” Workshops aim at guiding us toward unlocking our own truths by critically evaluating history, medicine, science and education. Dr. DeGruy shares her strategies for healing as well as encouraging others to discover their own. Dr. DeGruy has the keen ability to meet her audience where they are and inspire us to rise above our fears.

title: Info Session: Nicaragua/Mexico Study Abroad Spring 2017 (with "The Spanish-Speaking World")
body: During this information session, we will provide information on study abroad opportunities in Mexico and Nicaragua for the spring of 2017. Both study abroad opportunities are offered through the year-long program "The Spanish Speaking World," a program designed to integrate the intensive study of Spanish language with thematic study of Latin American, Spanish, and US-Latin@ literatures, histories, and cultures. In the spring, students have the opportunity to study in Mexico or Nicaragua for 10 weeks. The Santo Tomás, Nicaragua, program is coordinated with the Thurston-Santo Tomás Sister County Association (TSTSCA) and its counterpart in Nicaragua and is open to four to eight intermediate/advanced language students. The Mérida, Mexico option is coordinated with HABLA, the Center for Language and Culture, and is open to students of all language levels. During the information session, we will be joined by folks from both the TSTSCA and HABLA (via Skype) who can answer more questions about both programs, and will provide information on study abroad scholarships. All interested students are welcome.
